{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516727"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:46:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:46:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12711"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12711"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0.13,0.42,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108876"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5166"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91241"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1880"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2491"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9159"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42802"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43346"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108876"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing shortness of breath and fatigue. He used to be able to walk long distances without any issues, but now he has difficulty even walking up a flight of stairs. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He has a 15 pack-year smoking history but quit five years ago. He works as an accountant with no occupational exposures to dust or chemicals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears fatigued. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His jugular venous pressure is raised. Auscultation of the heart reveals a loud pulmonary component of the second heart sound. Auscultation of the lungs is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal an ECG showing evidence of right ventricular strain. His B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) level is 500 ng/L (\u003C100). Spirometry shows FEV1 3.2 L (85% predicted), FVC 4.0 L (90% predicted), FEV1/FVC ratio 80%, and TLCO 45% predicted. An echocardiogram shows right ventricular dilation with severe tricuspid regurgitation and an estimated pulmonary artery systolic pressure of 75 mmHg. Left ventricular function is normal. Mitral and aortic valves are normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA right heart catheterisation demonstrates a pulmonary capillary wedge pressure of 12 mmHg (6-12) and mean pulmonary artery pressure of 50 mmHg. A ventilation/perfusion scan shows no evidence of pulmonary emboli.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following will provide a survival benefit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Warfarin","Oxygen therapy","Digoxin","Bosentan","Furosemide"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation and investigations are consistent with pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH). The elevated BNP of 500 ng/L reflects right ventricular strain and is an important prognostic marker in PAH, with higher levels correlating with increased disease severity and mortality. The diagnosis of PAH is supported by the right heart catheterisation findings of elevated mean pulmonary artery pressure (\u003E20 mmHg) with normal pulmonary capillary wedge pressure (\u003C15 mmHg), excluding left heart disease as the cause. The spirometry showing normal FEV1/FVC ratio with isolated reduction in TLCO (45% predicted) is characteristic of pulmonary vascular disease rather than obstructive or restrictive lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary hypertension has five classes where the hypertension may be due to:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArterial disease (idiopathic, heritable, or drug-induced)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeft heart disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic lung disease and/or hypoxia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic thromboembolic pulmonary disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUncertain aetiology\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this patient, the most likely class is class I, or pulmonary arterial hypertension, given the absence of underlying lung or cardiac disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBosentan\u003C/strong\u003E is an endothelin receptor antagonist that has been shown to improve exercise capacity and survival in patients with PAH. It acts by blocking endothelin-1, a potent vasoconstrictor that plays a key role in the pathogenesis of PAH. It is an appropriate first-line treatment option for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin\u003C/strong\u003E may improve cardiac function in right heart failure but has not been shown to improve survival in PAH. While this patient has evidence of right ventricular strain (as indicated by the elevated BNP), targeting the underlying pulmonary vascular disease with specific PAH therapy is more appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may provide symptomatic relief in patients with hypoxaemia but does not modify disease progression or improve survival in PAH. This patient\u0027s oxygen saturation is relatively preserved at 95%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E anticoagulation is indicated in chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension but has no proven survival benefit in PAH. The normal ventilation/perfusion scan excludes chronic thromboembolism as the cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E may provide symptomatic relief of right heart failure but does not address the underlying pathology or improve survival in PAH. While this patient has elevated JVP suggesting right heart strain, specific PAH therapy is more appropriate than diuresis alone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Endothelin receptor antagonists improve exercise capacity and survival in patients with pulmonary arterial hypertension","Isolated reduction in TLCO with normal spirometry suggests pulmonary vascular disease rather than parenchymal lung disease","Right heart catheterisation is essential to confirm pulmonary arterial hypertension and exclude other causes"],"references":["Hassoun PM. Pulmonary Arterial Hypertension. N Engl J Med. 2021 Dec 16;385(25):2361-2376. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra2000348. PMID: 34910865.","Oldroyd SH, Manek G, Sankari A, et al. Pulmonary Hypertension. [Updated 2022 Dec 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482463/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91241"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12711"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91241"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-14T14:05:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-14T14:10:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5166"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108876"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"P